english:
  title: A Discourse on the Name 'Peaceful Source'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The disciple of Hyunam, Reverend Bun, has lived with Lazy Monk for several years now, and thus received from him the name 'Peaceful Source.' The monk's calligraphy remains fresh as new ink, and the landscape painting—a masterwork of Lazy Monk's finest inspiration—possesses a serene and distant beauty. Capped with a farewell verse of praise, one can see that Lazy Monk has left nothing untouched by his artistry. Since I am close to Hyunam, I did not refuse when he sought verses from me. Now he asks again for a discourse on Peaceful Source—how could I refuse such a request?

    If the Reverend has received so much from his teacher, surely there is much to say. Lazy Monk traveled through Jiangnan and inherited the dharma from Pingshan. Thus Ping is the very source from which Lazy Monk emerged, and the primordial nature reveals itself here. United in name, 'Peaceful Source' illuminates this truth: what he received from his teacher is no external thing, but merely his own original nature. The Buddha of heavenly purity knows neither change nor alteration, spanning past and present alike. Only through Pingshan's seal does this primordial source become manifest. How then can one speak lightly of the transmission between teacher and disciple? This is beyond my knowing.

    Consider the nature of water: it is wet and flows downward, pervading the dharma-realm. Yet its source emerges from heaven. Heaven is metal, and metal gives birth to water—thus rain and dew descend from above. When waters gather, they form the sea. Yet water also springs forth from ancient wells, from mountain peaks, from flying cascades and sheer cliffs, as if its source were suddenly cut off. Yet viewing this through water's virtue, it seeps and saturates the earth everywhere, leaving no place untouched. Hidden when it flows beneath the soil, revealed when it rises—wherever it goes, is it not level and peaceful?

    Moreso with this Reverend, who dwells contentedly within his station, neither swelling nor drying up, serene in lucid emptiness. The myriad things shimmer like a forest within him. How clearly does Lazy Monk know his people! Let the moon over the river scatter its reflections among them, and they play in realms of illusion as if in a painting. How could anyone follow where this Reverend goes? My admiration runs deep, and so I do not refuse but offer this humble discourse.
  footnotes:
    - Lazy Monk (나옹, Naeong) was a renowned Goryeo Buddhist monk and painter, known for his landscape paintings and calligraphy.
    - Pingshan (평산, Pingshan) represents the dharma transmission lineage, with 'Ping' (平) suggesting both the geographical origin and the concept of 'level' or 'peaceful' that becomes important to the discourse.
    - The discourse uses the metaphor of water and its source to explain the Buddhist concept of original nature and dharma transmission—water appears to emerge from various places but ultimately flows from heaven, just as all beings possess original buddha-nature.
    - Lee Saek (1328-1396) was a prominent Goryeo literatus, scholar, and official who played an important role in the transition from Goryeo to Joseon.
